WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.700
I want you to picture something, like, incredibly mundane for a second.

00:04.480 --> 00:05.600
Just indulge me here.

00:05.700 --> 00:06.600
Okay, I'm picturing it.

00:06.760 --> 00:10.460
Imagine you are sitting at your desk, you pull up an REPL environment,

00:10.760 --> 00:14.840
and you just pass a really basic arithmetic string to the interpreter.

00:15.000 --> 00:15.920
Like a calculator app.

00:15.980 --> 00:21.080
Exactly, like open parenthesis 2 plus 3, close parenthesis multiplied by 4.

00:21.200 --> 00:21.420
Right.

00:21.680 --> 00:25.620
You hit enter, the compilation executes, and bam, the integer 20 returns.

00:25.940 --> 00:26.660
Super simple.

00:26.780 --> 00:27.880
Very standard, yeah.

00:27.880 --> 00:30.600
Right, but now, put that environment aside,

00:30.940 --> 00:36.720
I want you to try and log in to an encrypted volume that you haven't, you know, mounted in 5 or 6 years.

00:36.840 --> 00:38.300
Oh, that is a terrible feeling.

00:38.360 --> 00:38.940
It's the worst.

00:39.020 --> 00:40.860
You sit there, you're staring at the passphrase prompt,

00:40.900 --> 00:45.900
and you're just feeling around in the dark for this specific sequence of characters that you know you generated.

00:46.000 --> 00:47.060
But it's just out of reach.

00:47.460 --> 00:47.860
Exactly.

00:48.280 --> 00:52.100
And the phenomenology of those two actions is completely misaligned.

00:52.160 --> 00:52.740
I mean, totally.

00:53.000 --> 00:57.700
One is this deterministic, instantaneous resolution of syntax, right?

00:57.700 --> 00:58.040
Mm-hmm.

00:58.040 --> 01:06.420
And the other is a highly visceral, almost physical sensation of navigating a degraded state space.

01:06.420 --> 01:08.800
Yeah, you can literally feel the effort.

01:09.300 --> 01:09.400
Right.

01:09.400 --> 01:15.800
And yet, conceptually, we tend to force both of those phenomenologies into the exact same architectural metaphor.

01:16.360 --> 01:20.960
We treat them both as operations interacting with a, like a storage box.

01:21.060 --> 01:22.140
The old hard drive analogy.

01:22.240 --> 01:22.700
Exactly.

01:23.120 --> 01:31.640
We assume the interpreter pulls operational values out of memory addresses, overwrites old states with new integers, and returns the result.

01:32.260 --> 01:36.820
And simultaneously, we model human memory as this biological rate array.

01:36.980 --> 01:42.800
Right. Assuming that forgetting a passphrase just means a cluster of data was zeroed out or, you know, corrupted in the box.

01:42.800 --> 01:46.520
Right. But what if that entire paradigm is just a complete hallucination?

01:47.080 --> 01:55.100
What if the way we construct computational logic and the way we model the degradation of human memory are both built on a fundamentally flawed ontology?

01:55.100 --> 01:58.360
Well, that is the exact premise of the sources we are looking at today.

01:58.480 --> 02:06.360
Yes. So, welcome to today's Deep Dive. We are digging into two monolithic 2026 monographs by the independent researcher, Flyxion.

02:06.640 --> 02:07.500
And they are dense.

02:07.920 --> 02:12.360
Oh, incredibly dense. But we're looking at the first one, Beyond Parentheses.

02:12.360 --> 02:34.580
These texts are, I mean, mathematically brutal, but they force a paradigm shift that is basically impossible to ignore once you actually grasp it.

02:34.580 --> 02:42.920
Our mission today is to map out this mind-bending shift. We are moving away from the idea of information as symbols in a storage box.

02:42.920 --> 02:49.100
Right. Because Flyxion is proposing that computation must be modeled as an irreversible, growing geometric history.

02:49.220 --> 02:49.940
Which is wild.

02:50.160 --> 03:01.120
It is. And that memory, whether biological or institutional, is not a hard drive. It's a physical landscape of repair paths that literally, like, geometrically deforms the moment you forget something.

03:01.120 --> 03:10.100
Okay, let's unpack this. Because if computation is no longer the manipulation of symbols in a mutable state, we basically have to rebuild our understanding of logic from the ground up.

03:10.200 --> 03:10.800
We really do.

03:11.140 --> 03:16.500
And Flyxion starts by targeting something we all learned in elementary school math, the parenthesis algorithm.

03:16.860 --> 03:20.120
Right. The foundational abstraction of all symbolic computations.

03:20.740 --> 03:24.900
Yeah. From basic math homework to highly complex compilers.

03:25.040 --> 03:28.200
Because the parenthesis algorithm is how we define scope and precedence.

03:28.320 --> 03:29.220
Right. PEMDES.

03:29.220 --> 03:39.380
Exactly. If you feed an interpreter a nested expression, say, three times, open parenthesis, two plus, open parenthesis, five times four, close, close, minus seven.

03:39.460 --> 03:40.880
That's a mouthful, but yeah.

03:41.080 --> 03:45.240
The compiler doesn't evaluate that linearly. It doesn't just read left to right.

03:45.340 --> 03:46.920
It looks for the deepest layer.

03:47.160 --> 03:56.760
Right. It locates the innermost bounded space, the five times four, evaluates it to 20, and essentially collapses that local scope, replacing it with the scalar result.

03:56.760 --> 03:59.260
It resolves the architecture from the inside out.

03:59.380 --> 04:00.280
Systematically, yes.

04:00.360 --> 04:07.860
But Flyxion isolates a massive architectural blind spot in how modern execution environments handle this process.

04:08.180 --> 04:10.980
It is what he terms the chalkboard mentality.

04:11.320 --> 04:15.160
The chalkboard mentality. Yeah, that is the defining characteristic of mutable state.

04:15.320 --> 04:17.380
Because when you do math on a chalkboard.

04:17.460 --> 04:22.620
Right. When an interpreter resolves that five times four into 20, it discards the operational history.

04:22.620 --> 04:24.680
You erase the intermediate steps.

04:24.780 --> 04:27.260
Exactly. It overwrites the memory registers.

04:28.040 --> 04:30.620
The system only cares about the transient current state.

04:31.380 --> 04:40.260
The intermediate steps, the specific geometric construction of how that 20 was actually derived, are aggressively zeroed out to free up heap space.

04:40.260 --> 04:52.800
So it's like, if traditional computing is like baking a cake, you put the ingredients in the oven, and the microsecond, the cake is baked, the recipe, the dirty mixing bowls, and the eggshells all just instantaneously vanish from the universe.

04:52.960 --> 04:53.660
Poof! Gone.

04:53.900 --> 05:00.540
You possess the final output, the cake, but you maintain absolutely zero topological record of the construction process.

05:00.680 --> 05:03.160
That is the standard execution model, yes.

05:03.280 --> 05:03.420
Yeah.

05:03.520 --> 05:07.700
And I mean, it works reasonably well for isolated, deterministic, single-threaded scripts.

05:07.860 --> 05:08.140
Sure.

05:08.140 --> 05:13.780
But Flyxion argues this deliberate amnesia completely obscures the actual geometry of computation.

05:14.920 --> 05:17.920
So to fix this, he introduces the sphere-pop calculus.

05:18.100 --> 05:18.620
Sphere-pop?

05:18.900 --> 05:25.480
Right. In sphere-pop, syntax isn't textual punctuation. It is explicit geometry. A parenthesis is modeled as a sphere.

05:25.640 --> 05:27.120
Like a literal 3D shape.

05:27.300 --> 05:31.120
Well, topologically, yes. It's a strictly autonomous geometric region.

05:31.120 --> 05:38.620
So when I instantiate a function, and, you know, open a parenthesis, I am spinning up an isolated local universe.

05:38.820 --> 05:45.040
Precisely. And the variables and operations inside that sphere are completely sealed off from the global scope.

05:45.100 --> 05:46.800
Okay, but then how do you get the answer out?

05:47.300 --> 05:54.480
Evaluation is no longer an act of rewriting a memory address. Evaluation is a geometric event called a pop.

05:54.480 --> 05:56.760
A pop. Like popping a bubble.

05:56.980 --> 06:01.440
Basically, yeah. A pop is the physical dissolution of that computational boundary.

06:02.020 --> 06:10.880
The spherepops, the localized boundary vanishes, and the coherent value produced inside is structurally integrated into the surrounding computational graph.

06:10.980 --> 06:13.660
Okay, wait. I need to push back on the hardware implementation here.

06:13.720 --> 06:14.380
I figured you might.

06:14.380 --> 06:26.620
Because if evaluation is just a pop that integrates a result into a growing graph, and we literally never overwrite or erase the intermediate steps, you are going to hit a physical hardware wall so fast.

06:26.800 --> 06:27.760
I mean, RAM is finite.

06:28.780 --> 06:36.320
Why on earth would we architect a system that intentionally generates a massive, infinitely growing topological trail of dirty mixing bowls?

06:36.420 --> 06:37.700
It sounds horribly inefficient.

06:37.860 --> 06:38.040
Yeah.

06:38.120 --> 06:39.780
It sounds impossible.

06:39.780 --> 06:45.600
How does Spearpop handle garbage collection without violating this core principle of immutable history?

06:46.020 --> 06:47.840
Well, that is the immediate engineering hurdle.

06:47.980 --> 06:48.160
Yeah.

06:48.320 --> 06:51.920
But you have to look at why Flyxion's retaining the history in the first place.

06:52.020 --> 06:52.660
Okay. Why?

06:52.860 --> 06:58.160
It is entirely about algorithmic provenance in non-deterministic environments.

06:58.800 --> 07:01.180
Provenance? Like the origin story of the data?

07:01.400 --> 07:01.920
Exactly.

07:02.760 --> 07:05.720
We don't live in a single-threaded deterministic world anymore.

07:05.720 --> 07:10.020
Our runtimes are highly concurrent, distributed, and probabilistic.

07:10.140 --> 07:12.420
Right. We have machine learning, distributed nodes.

07:12.480 --> 07:16.800
Exactly. So imagine node A and node B both output the integer five.

07:16.900 --> 07:17.120
Okay.

07:17.320 --> 07:24.380
But node A derived it from a strict cryptographic hash, and node B derived it from a low-confidence stochastic model.

07:24.500 --> 07:30.580
Oh, I see. A traditional mutable state system treats both of those fives as just identical integers.

07:30.860 --> 07:32.100
Right. It strips the context.

07:32.160 --> 07:33.560
That strips the provenance completely.

07:33.560 --> 07:42.980
Exactly. But in SpherePop, the history is the primary semantic object. You cannot separate a value from its geometric derivation.

07:43.560 --> 07:49.920
The five from node A and the five from node B are entirely different geometric entities because their histories are different.

07:50.040 --> 07:54.320
Okay. That makes sense for data integrity. But what about the hardware limit? The RAM issue?

07:54.520 --> 08:02.720
Right. So garbage collection in SpherePop isn't achieved by overriding active state. It is achieved by establishing irrestorability boundaries.

08:02.720 --> 08:04.720
Irrestorability boundaries.

08:04.900 --> 08:11.460
Yes. The runtime identifies subgraphs that can no longer topologically influence the active wavefront of computation.

08:11.700 --> 08:14.980
So parts of the math that literally can't affect the final answer anymore.

08:15.100 --> 08:23.760
Exactly. And it allows them to drop out of the admissibility manifold. It isn't deleting a file. It is along a causal chain to functionally decohere.

08:23.760 --> 08:30.840
Okay. So we are trading mutable state for an irreversible geometric history that provides absolute operational provenance.

08:31.040 --> 08:36.900
But if we can't aggressively overwrite memory registers, how do we handle variable assignment?

08:37.400 --> 08:40.960
Because, I mean, the bedrock of traditional programming is substitution.

08:41.520 --> 08:46.820
I assign a value to X and the compiler just substitutes that value wherever X is called.

08:46.820 --> 08:49.960
Well, substitution is fundamentally incompatible with SpherePop.

08:50.500 --> 08:53.920
Because substitution implies copying a transient state.

08:54.100 --> 08:58.360
Right. You can't just copy-paste a state if the state doesn't exist independently of its history.

08:58.940 --> 09:01.840
So Flyxion replaces substitution with replay.

09:02.080 --> 09:04.080
Replay. Let's get into the mechanics of replay.

09:04.440 --> 09:10.420
How does it differ from, say, a standard beta reduction in lambda calculus?

09:10.420 --> 09:16.840
Okay. So in lambda calculus, beta reduction literally replaces the bound variables with the argument.

09:17.140 --> 09:17.820
It rewrites it.

09:17.880 --> 09:21.240
Yes. It modifies the expression. Replay doesn't modify anything.

09:21.840 --> 09:26.420
Because the identity of an object in SpherePop is its value plus its specific historical derivation.

09:27.120 --> 09:28.440
So they are tied together forever.

09:28.640 --> 09:36.560
Exactly. When a function requires an argument, the runtime physically replays the historical sequence of computational events that produce that value.

09:36.600 --> 09:37.800
Yeah. It reruns the history.

09:37.800 --> 09:41.000
It reconstructs the admissible historical context.

09:41.180 --> 09:41.320
Yeah.

09:41.640 --> 09:47.180
You are dragging the entire causal provenance forward into the new evaluation.

09:47.500 --> 09:53.840
That is wild. But that significantly alters how we handle invalid operations or runtime errors, doesn't it?

09:54.100 --> 09:55.860
It changes everything about error handling.

09:55.860 --> 10:15.640
Because in standard architectures, if a script attempts an invalid operation, like a null pointer to reference or, I don't know, dividing by zero, the runtime attempts the execution, throws an exception, and then initiates a highly expensive stack unwinding process to panic and crash.

10:15.780 --> 10:22.240
Right. Because traditional architectures permit the system to enter an invalid state before realizing the state is invalid.

10:22.240 --> 10:25.060
You don't know it's a mistake until you've already written it on the talk board.

10:25.100 --> 10:29.380
Exactly. SpherePop circumvents it entirely through a mechanism called refusal.

10:29.740 --> 10:32.300
Refusal. So it evaluates admissibility before extension?

10:32.580 --> 10:41.420
Yes. Because history is immutable and cannot be overwritten, you simply cannot allow an incoherent operation to attach to the geometric graph.

10:41.420 --> 10:44.180
It's like blocking a bad Lego brick from snapping on.

10:44.180 --> 10:56.860
Exactly. The runtime evaluates the topological admissibility of a continuation. If a sphere attempts a geometrically invalid operation, the extension is simply refused.

10:57.320 --> 10:59.460
It never becomes part of the historical record.

10:59.580 --> 10:59.880
Never.

11:00.160 --> 11:08.980
The core graph remains completely pristine without the system ever having to dedicate CPU cycles to unwinding a corrupted stack.

11:08.980 --> 11:15.340
If we connect this to the bigger picture, the elegance of refusal is most apparent when we look at concurrency.

11:15.600 --> 11:22.060
Oh, this is the part that blew my mind. Because how does traditional software handle multiple threads operating simultaneously?

11:22.300 --> 11:24.000
With massive engineering headaches.

11:24.140 --> 11:29.700
Yeah. You have to write explicit threadlocks, mutexes, and semaphores just to prevent race conditions.

11:29.800 --> 11:33.940
Right. Ensuring two threads don't try to overwrite the same memory address at the exact same time.

11:34.120 --> 11:37.720
But all of those workarounds are just symptoms of the mutable state problem, aren't they?

11:37.720 --> 11:40.580
Exactly. And Flyxion solves this with the merge operator.

11:41.440 --> 11:48.180
So think about a directed acyclic graph representing our earlier math equation, but let's restructure it slightly.

11:48.900 --> 11:56.580
Imagine it's open parenthesis, 2 plus 3, close parenthesis, multiplied by open parenthesis, 4 plus 5, close parenthesis.

11:56.720 --> 12:03.600
Okay. So we have a parent multiplication sphere containing two distinct child spheres, the 2 plus 3 and the 4 plus 5.

12:03.600 --> 12:13.580
Right. Now textually, an interpreter might parse that sequentially left to right, but geometrically, those two child spheres share zero dependencies.

12:13.880 --> 12:20.220
Right. The addition of 4 and 5 does not require any input from the addition of 2 and 3. They are totally separate operations.

12:20.600 --> 12:28.820
Therefore, in spherepop, concurrency is not a feature you have to explicitly code. It is the natural geometric default of independent histories.

12:28.820 --> 12:31.400
Because they share no edges in the dependency graph, right?

12:31.400 --> 12:38.980
Exactly. Those spheres pop simultaneously. The merge operator simply allows topologically independent histories to evolve in parallel.

12:39.220 --> 12:41.920
No mutex is required because nothing is being overwritten.

12:42.220 --> 12:47.080
I was thinking about this, and it is so much like real life. It's like cooking a complex dinner.

12:47.080 --> 13:04.720
Well, you are reducing a sauce on the stove while your partner is setting the table. You aren't executing a single threaded synchronous loop where you stir the sauce once, pause, walk over and place one fork, pause, walk back and stir the sauce again.

13:04.840 --> 13:05.960
Right. That would be insane.

13:05.960 --> 13:19.420
You are executing a merge of independent causal histories. You are operating concurrently, and you only topologically combine those histories when the components are merged together at the end when dinner is served.

13:19.680 --> 13:24.540
That is an excellent way to visualize it. The geometry inherently dictates the execution timing.

13:24.540 --> 13:36.720
Okay, here's where it gets really interesting. We have this continuously expanding concurrent graph of popping spheres. We have replay dragging provenance forward and refusal maintaining structural integrity.

13:37.040 --> 13:37.120
Right.

13:37.140 --> 13:47.160
What is actually deciding the logic of those pops? Because in standard computing, if I am compiling, say, C++A, the execution engine and the logic of the language are tightly coupled.

13:47.160 --> 13:54.280
They are completely inseparable. The engine that moves the bits through the registers inherently knows what the bits represent.

13:54.560 --> 14:03.380
But Flyxion introduces something called the universal operator machine, the UOM, and this completely decouples the geometric graph from the logical execution.

14:03.920 --> 14:14.500
Yes. The UOM is arguably the most significant architectural breakthrough in the first text. Flyxion separates the execution engine from the operator logic entirely.

14:14.740 --> 14:16.620
Wait, how does an engine not know what it's executing?

14:16.620 --> 14:32.700
The UOM only knows how to navigate the geometry of the graph. That's it. It looks for spheres with resolved dependencies, pops them, extends the history, and routes the output. It is completely blind to the actual mathematical or logical meaning of the operations it is performing.

14:32.940 --> 14:40.820
Let me try an analogy here. It is like a train track system. The dependency graph of the spheres, the history, is the network of tracks.

14:40.820 --> 14:41.300
Okay.

14:41.520 --> 14:55.020
The UOM is the automated switching system. It routes the traffic, it prevents collisions, and it ensures continuous movement. But the UOM doesn't care what kind of train you place on those tracks. The operator library is the specific type of train you load onto the system.

14:55.020 --> 15:00.540
So the train analogy is close, but it actually breaks down when we factor in the concurrency we just discussed.

15:00.680 --> 15:01.620
Oh, really? Why?

15:01.800 --> 15:11.000
Because a train implies a fixed linear vehicle traversing a path. The UOM is much more like a propagating wavefront through a physical medium.

15:11.160 --> 15:11.840
A wavefront.

15:12.180 --> 15:24.080
Right. The wavefront advances based solely on the structural integrity of the medium, the graph. The operator library determines the frequency and amplitude of that wave, but the UOM just facilitates the physical propagation.

15:24.080 --> 15:30.700
Okay. I see the distinction. So if I instantiate the UOM and I plug in a strict Boolean operator library.

15:30.800 --> 15:40.260
Then an operational node labeled ANDD functions as a standard logical gate. True and true yields true. The wavefront propagates deterministically.

15:40.560 --> 15:46.220
Okay. But if I hot swap that library without changing the graph and inject a fuzzy logic library.

15:46.220 --> 15:50.780
The underlying geometric graph, the track, so to speak, doesn't change by a single vector.

15:51.000 --> 16:00.760
But now that exact same ANDD node computes degrees of truth. Instead of a binary true or false, it might output, say, a 0.72 certainty threshold.

16:01.140 --> 16:06.820
The UOM routes the data identically. But the semantics of the history have fundamentally shifted.

16:06.940 --> 16:13.240
And the application that makes this truly revolutionary. If I swap in a differentiable operator library.

16:13.240 --> 16:18.540
Then you instantly transition from a deterministic execution to a machine learning environment.

16:18.720 --> 16:19.200
Just like that.

16:19.360 --> 16:25.280
Just like that. The input nodes become continuous tensors. The operator spheres become activation functions.

16:25.680 --> 16:28.860
And most importantly, that replay mechanism we discussed earlier.

16:29.060 --> 16:35.120
Oh. Because it maintains the full causal history, it acts as the perfect architecture for backpropagation.

16:35.300 --> 16:39.900
Exactly. You traverse the replay history backward to calculate the gradients for descent.

16:39.900 --> 16:45.480
You have one singular universal operator machine evaluating a single geometric graph.

16:45.820 --> 16:54.320
And it is capable of executing Boolean logic, probabilistic reasoning, and deep neural network training purely by swapping the operator library.

16:54.460 --> 16:57.000
It is a stunning unification of computational logic.

16:57.460 --> 17:01.580
You aren't building disparate siloed execution engines for different tasks.

17:01.680 --> 17:06.080
You are simply altering the laws of physics inside a single geometric universe.

17:06.200 --> 17:07.080
It's beautiful, really.

17:07.080 --> 17:13.840
But this reliance on constructing and replaying history provides a rather dark bridge to Flyxion's second paper.

17:14.400 --> 17:14.680
It does.

17:15.060 --> 17:24.680
Because if the entire system is predicated on the capacity to replay or repair a causal chain, what happens to the geometry when that capacity is destroyed?

17:25.140 --> 17:36.300
What's fascinating here is that Flyxion takes this highly abstract calculus, which was designed for silicon environments, and seamlessly maps it onto biological and institutional observers.

17:36.300 --> 17:39.380
Which brings us to erasure is deformation.

17:39.840 --> 17:40.080
Yes.

17:40.840 --> 17:47.400
And he opens by entirely discarding the cognitive science consensus that memory is a storage mechanism.

17:47.460 --> 17:52.100
Returning to our opening discussion, memory is not a box in the brain where engrams are filed away.

17:52.220 --> 17:53.400
It is definitely not a box.

17:53.620 --> 17:56.740
Flyxion leans heavily into active inference models here.

17:56.740 --> 18:04.640
To remember a distinction, whether it is the visual differentiation between a predator and prey, or the syntactic structure of a cryptographic passphrase.

18:04.700 --> 18:06.380
Like the one we couldn't remember earlier.

18:06.520 --> 18:06.780
Right.

18:07.160 --> 18:09.580
Remembering that is not retrieving a static file.

18:09.780 --> 18:13.140
To remember is strictly defined as possessing the repair repertoire.

18:13.200 --> 18:14.080
Repair repertoire.

18:14.080 --> 18:14.520
Yes.

18:15.140 --> 18:22.820
It is the specific set of operators required to reconstruct that distinction after it has been perturbed by noise or time.

18:23.160 --> 18:23.300
Wait.

18:23.560 --> 18:26.820
So, forgetting isn't the deletion of a file.

18:27.000 --> 18:29.040
It's losing the tools to rebuild it.

18:29.220 --> 18:29.540
Correct.

18:29.540 --> 18:33.960
Your memory is defined by your capacity to repair access to a state.

18:34.180 --> 18:39.160
If you cannot repair the access, the state falls outside your universe of distinctions.

18:39.740 --> 18:42.900
And this physically alters the geometry of the observer's world.

18:42.900 --> 18:46.140
Flyxion calls this admissibility contraction, right?

18:46.300 --> 18:46.520
Yes.

18:47.120 --> 18:50.700
The observer's reality is strictly bounded by their admissibility.

18:51.200 --> 18:54.260
Manifold the total set of states they can successfully restore.

18:54.440 --> 18:54.700
Okay.

18:54.880 --> 18:56.780
When an operator is lost from the repertoire.

18:57.200 --> 18:59.940
An erasure event that manifold literally contracts.

19:00.620 --> 19:03.660
The universe of restorable distinctions geometrically shrinks inward.

19:04.260 --> 19:08.980
But if the boundaries of our internal world literally shrink when we forget, how is that quantified?

19:09.340 --> 19:11.860
Because Flyxion doesn't just use this as a poetic metaphor.

19:11.860 --> 19:14.260
He proves it using differential geometry.

19:14.460 --> 19:14.720
It does.

19:15.080 --> 19:18.420
He models this using what he calls the erasure deformation tensor.

19:18.540 --> 19:18.660
Okay.

19:18.820 --> 19:19.620
Break that down for me.

19:19.900 --> 19:29.520
So, he treats the admissibility manifold as a remaining in space, where the loss of a repair operator directly alters the local metric tensor of that space.

19:29.760 --> 19:30.060
Meaning?

19:30.380 --> 19:34.660
Meaning it isn't just that a region of memory is cordoned off or locked away.

19:34.660 --> 19:39.300
The actual geometry of the space warps and generates singularities.

19:39.720 --> 19:42.620
Let's ground this in the phenomenology of forgetting for a second.

19:42.760 --> 19:45.260
Think of a word that is on the tip of your tongue.

19:45.580 --> 19:45.760
Yeah.

19:45.960 --> 19:48.760
It takes immense mental energy to recall it.

19:49.020 --> 19:53.460
You are exerting, like, almost frustrating cognitive effort to retrieve it.

19:53.560 --> 19:53.800
Right.

19:53.920 --> 19:55.840
And that cognitive strain is not an illusion.

19:56.400 --> 20:01.380
It is the direct physical manifestation of the metric distortion calculated by the tensor.

20:01.380 --> 20:01.980
Really?

20:02.400 --> 20:02.660
Yes.

20:03.440 --> 20:11.960
As a specific memory approaches the boundary of your restorability as you lose the operators to reconstruct it, the metric distance to that memory stretches toward infinity.

20:12.180 --> 20:12.700
Oh, wow.

20:12.700 --> 20:19.100
The effort you feel is your cognitive apparatus attempting to drag its awareness across a severely deformed geometric space.

20:19.100 --> 20:22.720
The distance to the memory is literally stretching toward infinity.

